{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bf8939a6-f2f0-4c55-9998-7b42d9e96b8e","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01KqwNg6SoWGcZpKa2hgtWBm","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Answering MSTest SDK question"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01ATx8sSEBddTq3Rt4qFKf8T","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-de760926d54b43aca0b2f9409bf9ab31"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-de760926d54b43aca0b2f9409bf9ab31."}],"interactionId":"eaa97741-8c25-421d-8008-1139b19863c3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change when upgrading from MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0 to MSTest.Sdk/4.1.0, specifically related to test discovery with vstest.console. This is a knowledge question about MSTest SDK changes.\n\nLet me look at the files in the working directory to understand the context better, and also think about what I know about this change.\n\nFrom my knowledge: MSTest.Sdk 3.x included both the VSTest runner and the Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner by default. Starting with MSTest.Sdk 4.0, the VSTest compatibility layer was removed by default. The SDK now only ships with Microsoft.Testing.Platform as the test runner. This means `vstest.console` (which relies on the VSTest adapter) can no longer discover or run tests unless you explicitly opt back in.\n\n\nThe core issue is that `<EnableMicrosoftTestingPlatformVSTestBridge>` switched from defaulting to `true` in version 3.x to `false` in 4.x. To get vstest.console working again, you'd need to explicitly set that property back to `true` in your project file, or alternatively update your CI pipeline to use `dotnet test` with the newer Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner instead.","outputTokens":439,"requestId":"341C:1FCAB9:FE6FB:135A7F:69F4162F"},"id":"751274d8-50a6-46a6-8382-f9457fe9aaaa","timestamp":"2026-05-01T02:55:53.915Z","parentId":"604a83bf-b1d8-4ee8-8259-907bc72b2f4a"}
